<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Drip-irrigating-the-gardens-of-the-Sahel" title="Drip irrigating the gardens of the Sahel " alt="link">Drip irrigating the gardens of the Sahel </a></h2>

	
					<p> 
New Agriculturalist, February 2007. Beside a busy main road leading out of Ouagadougou, a patchwork of small plots provide leafy vegetables to the city markets. Tiendrebeogo Hamado, who previously grew vegetables for only seven months of the year, now grows lettuces and cabbages year round. The secret of his success lies in a low-pressure drip irrigation system that greatly reduces the drudgery of hand-carrying water, whilst increasing water efficiency. Like him, an increasing number of farmers across West Africa are adopting the system, known as the African Market Garden. In the dry areas, market gardens are commonly the only form of irrigated agriculture. And with the rapid increase in urban populations, a rising number of consumers are demanding a greater variety of fresh vegetables and fruit. Supplying perishable produce to urban areas, these gardens can be the basis of a productive and profitable business. </p>
							<p><span class="date">23/05/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Drip-irrigating-the-gardens-of-the-Sahel">Read more...</a>
</div>
