						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-rice-for-African-women" title="New rice for African women" alt="link">New rice for African women</a></h2>

	
					<p> Picture a field of rice: an expanse of bright green plants in flat, waterlogged land, the classic image of Asian rice farming. For African rice growers, however, the picture is changing fast. Upland rice varieties, grown on dry land, are expanding across the continent, spearheaded by the NERICAs, new varieties that offer the promise of high yields, short duration and disease resistance. Coordinating the campaign is the African Rice Initiative (ARI), a network hosted by the Africa Rice Center (WARDA). With funding of US$35 million from the African Development Bank, the ARI launched a programme in 2005 that targets a group of farmers already responsible for 80 per cent of rice production in Africa - women. (New Agriculturist, February 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-rice-for-African-women">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Africa-develops-common-science-and-technology-action-plan" title="Africa develops common science and technology action plan" alt="link">Africa develops common science and technology action plan</a></h2>

	
					<p> Africa has developed a consolidated action plan on science and technology that integrates the programmes and projects of the New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD) into the structures of the African Union. Africa’s Science and Technology Consolidated Plan of Action articulates Africa’s common objective of socio-economic transformation and full integration into the world economy. It reaffirms the continent’s commitment to collective action for developing and using science and technology to meet its objectives, and marks the start of an African process to strengthen scientific and technological capacities. The Plan of Action evolved from a series of regional and continental workshops involving a participatory process of consultations by African governments, scientists, policy makers, civil society and international partners. The plan places emphasis on developing an African system of research and technological innovation by establishing networks of centres of excellence dedicated to research and development, and capacity-building programmes. (Joseph Ngwawi, SARDC News Feature, 20 March 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Africa-develops-common-science-and-technology-action-plan">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Keep-modified-cassava-behind-glass-regulators" title="Keep modified cassava behind glass – regulators" alt="link">Keep modified cassava behind glass – regulators</a></h2>

	
					<p> The South African government has rejected an application by the country’s Agriculture Research Council (ARC) to conduct field trials of genetically modified (GM) cassava, saying it wants the ARC to first show that the plants are stable in contained greenhouse experiments. The GM cassava is designed to have high starch content for use in industrial purposes such as biofuel production and is not intended for human or animal consumption. The decision signals South African regulators’ careful scrutiny of proposed research in this controversial field. Although SA is one of only a handful of African countries with a legal framework governing GM crops, activists have charged that government lacks the capacity to enforce the rules. (Business Day, 22 March 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Keep-modified-cassava-behind-glass-regulators">Read more...</a>
</div>
