						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/UNIDO-DG-roots-for-biotech-biofuels-in-Africa" title="UNIDO DG roots for biotech, biofuels in Africa" alt="link">UNIDO DG roots for biotech, biofuels in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p> Speaking in Nairobi, Kenya, at the fourth monthly Open Forum for Agricultural Biotechnology (OFAB 4), UNIDO Director General Kandeh Yumkellah called on African scientists and leaders to make Africa a world leader in biofuels production. Yumkellah said Africa could produce enough cassava, palm oil, sugar cane, maize, trees, and other plants to produce biofuels for the continent and for export. In order for this to take place, he said, the right policies need to be put in place, scientists need to be give adequate support to conduct research, and strong public and private partnerships must be formed to marshal new technologies and investments. It would be sad for scientists in Africa, including those serving under the CGIAR, just to &quot;sit back,&quot; only for them to come back 15 years later to conduct retrogressive research on how and why Africa lost again in the on-going agricultural biotechnology and biofuels revolutions. He promised UNIDO support and asked the African Agricultural Technology Foundation (AATF) to help rally African farmers, scientists, and leaders for a sustainable agricultural revolution so that Africa can be food secure and also produce surplus for biofuels' generation. (Crop Biotech Update, 10 February 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/UNIDO-DG-roots-for-biotech-biofuels-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Are-EU-GMO-rules-starving-the-poor" title="Are EU GMO rules starving the poor?" alt="link">Are EU GMO rules starving the poor?</a></h2>

	
					<p> A debate organised by Friends of Europe, an EU policy think-tank, explored whether the EU's strict authorisation procedures on genetically modified food are preventing developing countries from investing in potentially lifesaving technologies. Green NGOs in attendance rejected this idea. But Danish Environment Minister Connie Hedegaard said that developing countries' inability to export GMOs to the EU discourages them from investing in and producing crop that could help solve the problem of hunger. Per Pindstrup-Andersen (IFPRI), agreed, saying that Europe is standing in the way of developing countries solving their own problems. Simon Barber, of EuropaBio, the European Association for Bioindustries, commented that the European public has &quot;very limited knowledge&quot; about GMOs and about agriculture in general, and he accused green groups of spreading unfounded rumors. Friends of Europe director Fouad Hamdan disagreed with the idea that NGOs are stirring up fear on false pretences. &quot;I still believe that the benefits of GM food are almost nil … NGOs are working with independent scientific facts, not with biotech-industry funded research.&quot; He added that &quot;The EU can with a lot of confidence tell developing countries to be cautious [on GMOs] too. The organic market is the future.&quot; (Euractiv, February 2007)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Are-EU-GMO-rules-starving-the-poor">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Coexistence-genetically-modified-biotechnologies-and-biosafety-implications-for-developing-countries" title="Coexistence, genetically modified biotechnologies and biosafety: implications for developing countries" alt="link">Coexistence, genetically modified biotechnologies and biosafety: implications for developing countries</a></h2>

	
					<p> This article discusses the potential for developing countries in Asia and Africa to adopt systems for the &quot;coexistence&quot; of genetically modified (GM), conventional, and organic crops. It concludes that in Asia but &quot;much less&quot; in Africa &quot;there may be limited opportunities&quot; to implement coexistence as a formal, government-sponsored or -mediated production system. The main problem, it says, is one of capacity. The article identifies the key &quot;stumbling blocks&quot; for the development of African and Asian segregation, traceability, and identity preservation (STIP) systems as: 1) the need for capacity to implement these systems; 2) the capacity of legal systems to address the issue of liability; and 3) the capacity of other governance institutions to govern the different components attached to a coexistence system. An important unanswered question is who would bear the costs of STIP systems. Few studies, it says, have examined the impact of mandatory food labelling in developing countries. In the future, the development of coexistence systems in Africa and Asia will be closely associated with the growth of the organic farming sector. Thus far, Asian and African systems for segregating organic produce have resulted from privately developed standards and contractual agreements, not government regulations. (José Falck Zepeda, American Journal of Agricultural Economics, 88(5): 1200–1208)</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Coexistence-genetically-modified-biotechnologies-and-biosafety-implications-for-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
